{{Indonesia-stub}}

'''Clergy Reserves''' were tracts of land in [[Upper Canada]] and [[Lower Canada]] reserved for the support of "[[Protestantism|Protestant]] [[clergy]]" by the [[Constitutional Act of 1791]].<ref>{{Cite canlaw|short title  =An Act to repeal certain Parts of an Act, passed in the Fourteenth Year of His Majesty's Reign, intituled, An Act for making more effectual Provision for the Government of the Province of Quebec, in North America, and to make further Province for the Government of the said Province|abbr =|year =31 Geo. III|chapter =31|section = 36{{endash}}37|link= https://archive.org/stream/cihm_21241#page/n16/mode/1up}}</ref> One-seventh of all surveyed Crown lands were set aside,{{sfn|Lindsey|Rolph|1851|p=3}} totalling {{convert|2395687|acre|km2|0}} and {{convert|934052|acre|km2|0}} respectively for each Province,{{sfn|Lindsey|Rolph|1851|p=3}} and provision was made to dedicate some of those reserved lands as [[glebe|glebe land]] in support of any [[parsonage]] or [[rectory]] that may be established by the [[Church of England]].<ref>31 Geo. III, c. 31, s. 38{{endash}}40</ref> The provincial legislatures could vary or repeal these provisions, but [[royal assent]] could not be given prior to such passed bills having been laid before both houses of the [[British Parliament]] for at least thirty days.<ref>31 Geo. III, c. 31, s. 41{{endash}}42</ref>

==Upper Canada==
{{main|Upper Canada}}
The first lieutenant governor of Upper Canada, [[John Graves Simcoe]], interpreted "Protestant clergy" to mean the clergy of [[Church of England]] only.{{sfn|Lindsey|Rolph|1851|p=4}} However, in 1823 the [[Law Officers of the Crown]] held that the [[Church of Scotland]] was also entitled to a share of the revenues under the 1791 Act.{{sfn|Lindsey|Rolph|1851|p=9}} Although [[Peregrine Maitland|Lt-Governor Maitland]] attempted to suppress the publication of that decision, the Legislature passed resolutions the following year that recognized that church's status.{{sfn|Fahey|1991|pp=75}}
[[File:Johnstrachan.JPG|thumb|right|[[John Strachan]]]]
Complications in establishing leasing procedures prevented the reserve lands from being leased before 1803.{{sfn|Wilson|1969|p=9}} Until 1819, the reserve lands were managed by the Province, and in most years they earned revenues that were barely sufficient to cover their expenses.{{sfn|Ryerson|1884|p=220}} After the Rev. [[John Strachan]] was appointed to the [[Executive Council of Upper Canada]] in 1815, he began to push for the Church of England's autonomous control of the clergy reserves on the model of the Clergy Corporation created in Lower Canada in 1817. The [[Clergy Corporation]], of which Strachan became the chairman,{{sfn|Schrauwers|2009|p=3}}  was subsequently incorporated in 1819 to manage the Clergy Reserves.

The 1819 charter (drafted by Strachan's former student, Attorney General [[John Beverly Robinson]]){{sfn|Wilson|1959|p=135}} provided for the Bishop of Quebec to become the perpetual Principal and Director (as he was for the Lower Canada body), who, with twelve other directors, constituted the Board. The Bishop's Official (named by the Bishop) and the rectors of Niagara and York could each serve as acting chairman.

Other perpetual directors were:{{sfn|Wilson|1959|p=137}}

:* the incumbents at Kingston, Niagara, York, Cornwall, Grimsby, Ancaster and Hamilton; and
:* the Inspector General and Surveyor General of the Province of Upper Canada.

Any two directors, together with the Principal or an acting chairman, constituted a quorum,{{sfn|Wilson|1959|p=137}} but, because of the poor network of roads, most clergy members were generally unable to attend Corporation meetings.{{sfn|Schrauwers|2009|p=25}} This effectively meant that Strachan (as rector of York), together with the Inspector General and Surveyor General, controlled the Board.{{sfn|Wilson|1959|p=139}} These three members were part of the [[Family Compact]], of which Strachan was the leader.{{sfn|Schrauwers|2009|p=24}}

The reserves were allotted in [[Land lot|lots]] of {{convert|200|acre|ha|0}}, generally intermixed with other lots sold to individuals within each surveyed [[Township (Canada)|township]].{{sfn|Lindsey|Rolph|1851|p=3}} Except in the [[Thomas Talbot (Upper Canada)|Talbot Settlement]] (where they were located off the main roads), they were generally arranged in a [[checkerboard]] pattern within each township,{{sfn|Wilson|1969|pp=7{{endash}}8}} and were a serious obstacle to economic development as they were effectively [[wiktionary:wasteland|wasteland]],{{sfn|Hayes|2004|p=61}} either being abandoned by lessees after the timber had been fully harvested,{{sfn|Wilson|1969|p=9}} or unattractive because of the availability of cheap freehold land.{{sfn|Wilson|1969|p=9}} This was recognized by the Legislative Assembly in 1817 when it passed resolutions that condemned the lands as "insurmountable obstacles" and called on Westminster to authorize their sale.{{sfn|Fahey|1991|pp=74}}

Until 1827, no reserve lands were sold.{{sfn|Lindsey|Rolph|1851|p=8}} They were leased for terms of twenty-one years, with rents on a [[sliding scale]]:{{sfn|Lindsey|Rolph|1851|p=8}}

{| class="wikitable"
|+ Lease terms for clergy reserve lands (1791-1819)
|-
! Period !! Granted before April 1811 !!Granted from April 1811 !! Area covered
|-
|First 7 years ||align="right"| 10''s''.||align="right"|£1 15''s''. ||rowspan="3"|per lot of {{convert|200|acre|ha|0}} or less
|-
|Next 7 years ||align="right"| 20''s''.||align="right"|£3 10''s''.
|-
|Last 7 years ||align="right"|£1 10''s''.||align="right"|£5 5''s''.
|}

Even with higher rates being charged from 1819, total annual revenues were still only £1200 in 1824, and only one-third could be collected without pursuing legal action.{{sfn|Lindsey|Rolph|1851|p=8}}

In 1826, the [[Canada Company]] was formed to sell off the remaining crown and clergy reserves in the province.<ref>{{Cite canlaw|short title =An Act to enable his Majesty to grant to a company, to incorporated by charter, to be called "The Canada Company", certain lands in the province of Upper Canada, and to invest the said company with certain powers and privileges, and other privileges relating thereto|abbr =|year =6 Geo. IV|chapter =75|link=https://books.google.com/books?id=zsYvAAAAIAAJ&lpg=PA618&ots=bxcoxe59rA&pg=PA618#v=onepage&f=false}}</ref> However, because of opposition from Strachan,{{sfn|Fahey|1991|pp=64}} the Company received {{convert|1100000|acre|km2|0}} in the [[Huron Tract]], in substitution for the originally contemplated {{convert|829430|acre|km2|0}} of clergy reserve lands.{{sfn|Lee|2004|pp=39}} As the provincial policy of free [[land grant]]s had come to an end, Strachan lobbied for and secured an Act from the British Parliament granting authority to sell up to one-fourth of all reserve lands, up to {{convert|100000|acre|km2|0}} each year,<ref>{{Cite canlaw|short title =An Act to authorize the sale of a part of the clergy reserves in the provinces of Upper and Lower Canada|abbr =|year =7-8 Geo. IV|chapter =62|link=https://books.google.com/books?id=zsYvAAAAIAAJ&lpg=PA618&ots=bxcoxe59rA&pg=PA641#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> from which there would be income sufficient to support 200{{endash}}300 Anglican clergymen.{{sfn|Fahey|1991|pp=64}}

In 1836, before [[John Colborne, 1st Baron Seaton|Sir John Colborne]] was succeeded by [[Sir Francis Bond Head]] as lieutenant-governor, he created 57 rectories for the Church of England, with glebe land totalling {{convert|21057|acre|km2|0}}.{{sfn|Lindsey|Rolph|1851|pp=29{{endash}}30}} This action created significant political dissent,{{sfn|Lindsey|Rolph|1851|pp=30{{endash}}31}} and was subsequently declared illegal in 1837,{{sfn|Lindsey|Rolph|1851|p=31}} but was later held in 1856 to have been lawful.{{sfn|Ryerson|1884|p=224}}<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/cihm_89291#page/n493/mode/1up ''Attorney-General v. Grasett''], (1857) 6 Gr. 200</ref> In the interim, it became one of the issues in the [[Upper Canada Rebellion]] of 1837 (and subsequently identified as such in [[Report on the Affairs of British North America|the 1838 report]] written by [[John Lambton, 1st Earl of Durham|Lord Durham]]),{{sfn|Hayes|2004|p=61}} where [[William Lyon Mackenzie]] exclaimed to the crowd outside [[Montgomery's Tavern]]:

{{cquote|
Stick true to the cause of Liberty, and you shall, every man of you, have three hundred Acres of Land and a piece out of the Clergy Reserves!{{sfn|Wilson|1969|p=18}}
}}

The [[Legislative Assembly of Upper Canada]] passed a law to sell the reserves in 1840,{{sfn|Lindsey|Rolph|1851|pp=41{{endash}}42}} but it was [[disallowance and reservation|disallowed]]{{sfn|Lindsey|Rolph|1851|pp=43{{endash}}44}} and displaced by an Imperial Act passed later in that year.<ref>{{Cite canlaw|short title =An Act to provide for the Sale of the Clergy Reserves in the Province of Canada, and for the Distribution of the Proceeds thereof|abbr =|year =3-4 Vic.|chapter =78|link=https://archive.org/stream/cihm_41745#page/n5/mode/2up}}</ref> Although considered to be more favourable to the Church of England,{{sfn|Lindsey|Rolph|1851|pp=45{{endash}}48}} the Act as passed provided that only one-half of future sales would be dedicated on a 2:1 basis to the Churches of England and Scotland, with the remaining half being distributed to all other churches according to their respective strengths.{{sfn|Wilson|1969|p=19}} The administration of the reserve lands was transferred to the [[Commissioner of Crown Lands (Province of Canada)|Crown Lands Department]], where it was handled in a more professional manner.{{sfn|Wilson|1969|p=19}}

==Lower Canada==
[[File:Jacob Mountain, 1st Lord Bishop of Quebec,1778.jpg|thumb|left|Bishop [[Jacob Mountain]]]]
Unlike the distribution of lots that was pursued by Simcoe in Upper Canada, [[Alured Clarke]], [[List of lieutenant governors of Quebec|lieutenant-governor of Lower Canada]], instituted a policy of setting aside large blocks of land apart from either current or contiguous settlement.{{sfn|Wilson|1969|p=7}}

The Clergy Corporation in Lower Canada, more formally known as the "Corporation for Superintending, Managing and Conducting the Clergy Reserves within the Province of Lower-Canada", was constituted with the [[Anglican Diocese of Quebec|Bishop of Quebec]] (initially the Right Rev. [[Jacob Mountain]]) as perpetual Principal and Director, and with rectors of four parishes within the diocese constituted as perpetual directors.<ref>{{cite web|title = By-laws, made, ordained and constituted by the Corporation for Superintending, Managing and Conducting the Clergy Reserves within the Province of Lower-Canada on Wednesday the 1st day of March, in the year of Our Lord Christ 1820|url = https://archive.org/stream/cihm_91242#page/n4/mode/1up|publisher = archive.org}}</ref> In 1828, a British parliamentary committee reported that leases were being granted on certain terms:

{| class="wikitable"
|+ Lease terms for clergy reserve lands in Lower Canada per 200-acre lot (1828)
|-
! Period !! Rent in specie !!Rent in kind, in the alternative
|-
|First 7 years ||align="right"| 25''s''.||align="right"|8 bushels of wheat
|-
|Next 7 years ||align="right"|£2 10''s''.||align="right"|16 bushels
|-
|Last 7 years ||align="right"|£3 15''s''.||align="right"|24 bushels
|}

The reserve lands generated little income in Lower Canada, with the average annual profit from such activity amounting to only £3 between 1791 and 1837.{{sfn|Hayes|2004|p=60}}

==Abolition==
Pressure arose to reform the entire structure of the reserves, but the government of [[Robert Baldwin]] and [[Louis-Hippolyte Lafontaine]] chose not to proceed on such a course, because of the resistance of the established churches and the roadblocks presented by the 1791 Act.{{sfn|Wilson|1969|p=20}} However, such caution eventually came to be seen as inflexibility, which would be overcome by the rise of the [[Clear Grits|Grit movement]] in 1850.{{sfn|Wilson|1969|p=20}}

Even as late as 1853, Strachan was still campaigning to ensure the Church of England's dominance in the matter. As he stated in a letter to [[Henry Pelham-Clinton, 5th Duke of Newcastle|Lord Newcastle]]:

{{cquote|
Can religious liberty be preserved in no other way than by putting all religions on a level, as equally entitled for support from public encouragement and protection ? Are the Koran, the Vedas, the book of the Mormons, and the Holy Bible, to be held equally sacred ? And are the public authorities, the organs by which the nation acts, to take any of these indifferently as the rule to direct them in their public proceedings ? And in a nation of Protestants, who have high and peculiar interests to preserve and transmit to posterity, are all places of power and trust, and even the Throne itself, to be open equally to the Atheist, the Infidel, the Pagan, the Mussulman, the Romanist, the Mormon and the Protestant ? Is the kingdom of Satan, in whatever shape it may appear, lo enjoy the same public favor as the Kingdom of God ? Is a Christian Church, a Pagan temple, and a mosque, to be equally held in honor? In one word, is "the freedom of the City to be bestowed on all the gods of mankind?"{{sfn|Strachan|1853|pp=26{{endash}}27}}
}}

Following the victory of [[Augustin-Norbert Morin]] and [[Allan MacNab]] in the [[List of elections in the Province of Canada#1854|1854 general election]], in conjunction with the abolition of [[Seigneurial system of New France|seigneurial tenure]] in [[Lower Canada]],{{sfn|Wilson|1969|p=21}} the lands were finally removed from church control and secularized under an Act of the [[Legislative Assembly of the Province of Canada]],{{sfn|Fahey|1991|pp=175}}<ref>{{Cite canlaw|short title  =An Act to make better provision for the appropriation of Moneys arising from the lands heretofore known as the Clergy Reserves, by rendering them available for Municipal purposes|abbr =S.Prov.C.|year =1854|chapter =2|link= https://books.google.com/books?id=3CpCAQAAMAAJ&lpg=RA1-PA85&ots=eQbEuFPoNi&pg=RA1-PA4#v=onepage&f=false}}</ref> under which:{{sfn|Fahey|1991|pp=175}}

:* sales and other revenues from the reserves were constituted as separate funds dedicated to municipal purposes in Upper and Lower Canada,<ref>S.Prov.C. 1854, c. 2, s. 1</ref> and
:* recipients of stipends could cede their life claims to their respective churches, which could in turn commute the sums of such claims at 6% ''[[per annum]]''.<ref>S.Prov.C. 1854, c. 2, s. 3</ref>

==Impact and aftermath==
Reform of the Clergy Reserves was a major issue in Canadian politics from its creation until its abolition. The controversy stemmed from the fact that many supporters of the religious endowment were part of the Tory ruling class. Even [[Robert Baldwin]], who was the leader of the struggle for [[Responsible Government]] did not advocate for complete abolition and chose to resign his seat rather than tackle the question.

In 1867, the Municipalities Funds for Upper and Lower Canada were declared to be part of the joint property of the new provinces of Ontario and Quebec,<ref>{{Cite canlaw|short title  =British North America Act, 1867|abbr =|year =30 & 31 Vic.|chapter =3|schedule=IV|link=http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/Const/page-12.html}}</ref> subject to division and adjustment at a later date by arbitrators appointed under s. 142 of the ''[[Constitution Act, 1867|British North America Act, 1867]]''. The funds were awarded to each province respectively in September 1870,<ref>{{cite web|title = Sessional Paper No. 9: Copy of the Award of the Arbitrators between the Provinces of Upper Canada and Lower Canada, referred to in the second paragraph of the Speech from the Throne. Transmitted to the Legislative Assembly by the Lieutenant Governor.|url = https://archive.org/stream/n02ontariosession03ontauoft#page/n413/mode/2up|publisher = Legislative Assembly of Ontario|at= par. 3 and 5|date = December 16, 1870}}</ref> and the award itself was held to be valid by the [[Judicial Committee of the Privy Council]] in March 1878.<ref>{{cite book|title = At the Court of Windsor|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=v2hOAAAAMAAJ&lpg=RA6-PA10&ots=kk5G_3eyLo&pg=RA3-PA79#v=onepage&f=false|date = March 26, 1878}}</ref> In Ontario, the Fund continued to be accounted for separately until the passage of an Act in 1908, where all special funds were declared to form part of the province's Consolidated Revenue Fund.<ref>{{Cite canlaw|short title  =The Consolidated Revenue Fund Act, 1908|abbr =S.O.|year =1908|chapter =10|link=https://archive.org/stream/statutesofprovin1908onta#page/176/mode/2up}}</ref>

